  "prompt": "Can you get the flu even after vaccination?",
  "response": "Yes, you can still get the flu even after being vaccinated. Here's why:\n\n*   **The flu vaccine isn't 100% effective:** Flu vaccines are designed to protect against the flu viruses that research indicates will be most common during the upcoming season. However, their effectiveness varies from year to year depending on how well the vaccine matches the circulating flu viruses.\n*   **There are many flu viruses:** The flu vaccine typically protects against three or four different flu viruses (depending on whether it's a trivalent or quadrivalent vaccine). There are many other flu viruses that aren't included in the vaccine, and you can still get sick from those.\n*   **Timing of the vaccine:** It takes about two weeks after vaccination for your body to develop antibodies that protect against the flu. If you're exposed to the flu virus before or during that time, you can still get sick.\n*   **You might have caught a different virus:** Many other viruses can cause symptoms similar to the flu, such as a cold or respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). You might think you have the flu, but it could be something else entirely.\n\n**Important note:** Even if you get the flu after vaccination, the vaccine can still help reduce the severity of your illness and lower your risk of complications, such as pneumonia or hospitalization.",
